# Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this React + Vite project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed Package
- Added `@vercel/analytics` v2.0.1 to project dependencies
- Used npm to install the package (matching the project's existing package manager)

### 2. Modified Files

**src/App.jsx**
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/react';`
- Added `<Analytics />` component at the end of the App component's JSX return, just before the closing div
- Follows the official Vercel documentation for React/Vite projects

**package.json & package-lock.json**
- Updated with the new @vercel/analytics dependency
- Lock file updated to ensure consistent dependency resolution

## Implementation Details

According to the official Vercel Analytics documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart), for React projects using Vite, the Analytics component should be imported from `@vercel/analytics/react` and placed within the main App component.

The Analytics component was strategically placed at the end of the App's return statement to ensure it doesn't interfere with the existing UI while properly tracking page views and user interactions.

## Verification

✅ Build completed successfully with no errors
✅ No new linting errors introduced (pre-existing lint warnings remain unchanged)
✅ Package installed correctly
✅ Code follows React best practices and the project's existing patterns

## Next Steps

To see analytics data in your Vercel dashboard:
1. Enable Web Analytics for your project in the Vercel dashboard (Settings → Analytics)
2. Deploy the application to Vercel
3. Once deployed and users visit the site, analytics data will appear in the dashboard

The analytics will work automatically once deployed to Vercel - no additional configuration needed.
